00:19.848 --> 00:21.566
[narrator] <i>For over a century,</i>

00:21.641 --> 00:25.603
<i>the Roman Coliseum has hosted the
most grueling and bloody games</i>

00:25.604 --> 00:26.946
<i>in human history,</i>

00:27.230 --> 00:30.742
<i>fought and won by the Roman gladiator.</i>

00:32.110 --> 00:35.080
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:02.349 --> 01:04.608
<i>At the end of the second century,</i>

01:05.310 --> 01:08.863
<i>the Roman people witness
a game like no other.</i>

01:13.151 --> 01:15.236
<i>For the first time in history,</i>

01:15.237 --> 01:19.082
<i>a Roman Emperor will fight to the death.</i>

01:23.370 --> 01:26.622
[announcer] All hail Commodus,

01:26.623 --> 01:29.551
Emperor of Rome!

01:46.601 --> 01:49.529
♪ ♪

02:42.282 --> 02:43.708
[screams]

02:47.037 --> 02:49.214
[cheers]

02:56.922 --> 03:00.549
[narrator] <i>Commodus's reign will
mark the beginning of the fall...</i>

03:00.550 --> 03:03.395
<i>of the greatest civilization on Earth.</i>

03:04.721 --> 03:08.191
<i>But his story begins more
than a decade earlier.</i>

03:14.022 --> 03:17.117
[theme music playing]

04:26.631 --> 04:30.717
<font color="#007700">Synced and corrected by Aaronnmb</font>
www.addic7ed.com

04:44.821 --> 04:47.165
[narrator] <i>By the end
of the second century,</i>

04:48.325 --> 04:54.714
<i>there's no civilization as massive
or as powerful as the Roman Empire.</i>

04:54.915 --> 05:00.136
<i>Almost one in five people on Earth
lives within the Empire's boundaries...</i>

05:06.385 --> 05:10.522
<i>and is under rule of one of the
most powerful men on the planet,</i>

05:12.683 --> 05:16.111
<i>the Roman Emperor Marcus Aurelius.</i>

05:24.736 --> 05:26.404
<i>For more than a decade,</i>

05:26.405 --> 05:30.417
<i>Aurelius has waged war to
defend the Empire's reach.</i>

05:35.998 --> 05:40.093
<i>And he reigns over a territory
that spans thousands of miles.</i>

05:40.293 --> 05:42.837
<i>From Western Europe and the Middle East,</i>

05:42.838 --> 05:47.517
<i>through parts of Africa and
the entire Mediterranean.</i>

05:53.223 --> 05:54.640
[Prof. Corey Brennan]
<i>Marcus Aurelius was</i>

05:54.641 --> 05:57.810
considered really one of
the most successful Emperors.

05:57.811 --> 06:01.990
<i>He was not just Emperor, but he
was a distinguished philosopher.</i>

06:02.482 --> 06:04.734
<i>He was a student of Epictetus,</i>

06:04.735 --> 06:06.777
who was the leading Stoic
philosopher of the day,

06:06.778 --> 06:10.573
and he was a gifted philosophical
writer in his own right.

06:10.574 --> 06:12.834
<i>His meditations are still read today.</i>

06:19.833 --> 06:21.584
[narrator] <i>Over the last century,</i>

06:21.585 --> 06:24.337
<i>Rome has been built into one
of the most advanced cities</i>

06:24.338 --> 06:26.139
<i>in the ancient world.</i>

06:27.049 --> 06:29.184
<i>And, under Aurelius's reign,</i>

06:29.217 --> 06:31.353
<i>it's given rise to a modern era.</i>

06:33.764 --> 06:36.358
[Tom Holland] <i>The Roman Empire</i>
<i>in the second century</i>

06:36.475 --> 06:40.487
was a formidable global superpower.

06:40.896 --> 06:44.574
<i>They had the most
proficient military forces.</i>

06:44.691 --> 06:48.912
<i>They ruled the most
civilized array of people.</i>

06:49.112 --> 06:53.324
<i>There was anything that you
wanted by Roman standards,</i>

06:53.325 --> 06:55.159
you could find in their empire.

06:55.160 --> 06:57.828
And what kept this empire together

06:57.829 --> 07:03.385
was an incredibly efficient
array of infrastructure.

07:05.045 --> 07:06.916
[Prof. Marden Nichols] <i>Ancient
Rome during this time period</i>

07:06.917 --> 07:10.183
<i>was the greatest empire that
the world had ever known.</i>

07:10.467 --> 07:16.639
<i>It was responsible for
enormous advances in technology</i>

07:16.640 --> 07:22.612
<i>such as the system of Roman roads or
the aqueducts that supplied water.</i>

07:23.105 --> 07:27.108
The city of Rome itself had
reached one million people.

07:27.109 --> 07:28.618
So it was the first

07:28.902 --> 07:32.163
<i>large-scale urban metropolis.</i>

07:33.657 --> 07:37.076
[narrator] <i>Marcus Aurelius</i>
<i>rules over 50 million people</i>

07:37.077 --> 07:39.754
<i>within the boundaries
of the Roman Empire.</i>

07:45.877 --> 07:48.471
<i>And no one lives better than his son...</i>

07:49.214 --> 07:50.724
<i>Commodus.</i>

07:57.264 --> 08:01.684
[Holland] <i>The problem that was</i>
<i>ushered in by Marcus Aurelius</i>

08:01.685 --> 08:05.187
when instead of doing what
his predecessors had done,

08:05.188 --> 08:08.941
and adopting a person who was qualified

08:08.942 --> 08:12.695
<i>by temperament, and upbringing,
and training to serve as Emperor,</i>

08:12.696 --> 08:16.207
<i>instead wanted his son to succeed him.</i>

08:17.909 --> 08:20.578
[Nichols] <i>Commodus was
the first Roman Emperor</i>

08:20.579 --> 08:24.424
who was ever born to a sitting emperor.

08:26.001 --> 08:27.752
<i>Growing up the son of an emperor,</i>

08:27.753 --> 08:33.341
<i>as someone who was raised from
birth to succeed his father,</i>

08:33.342 --> 08:37.845
we have to imagine that
Commodus's ego had no place to go.

08:37.846 --> 08:40.347
<i>Knowing that he would have this role,</i>

08:40.349 --> 08:43.476
<i>that this had planted
some seed in his mind</i>

08:43.477 --> 08:46.112
<i>that he was, in some
sense, extraordinary.</i>

09:16.718 --> 09:18.150
Commodus.

09:18.303 --> 09:19.553
- [groans]
- [sighs]

09:19.554 --> 09:21.143
Go.

09:23.725 --> 09:25.068
Good morning, Mother.

09:25.602 --> 09:27.104
Now.

09:32.651 --> 09:34.536
Do you know what time it is?

09:35.529 --> 09:36.663
Early.

09:38.156 --> 09:39.740
I'm sending you to Germania.

09:39.741 --> 09:41.710
What? Why?

09:42.911 --> 09:45.797
Because all you do here is
drink and play with whores.

09:46.081 --> 09:47.924
But there's a war.

09:49.334 --> 09:51.136
It'll teach you discipline.

09:53.505 --> 09:55.006
I'm not going anywhere.

09:55.007 --> 09:56.891
It's already been decided.

09:57.968 --> 09:59.728
Your father's expecting you.

10:07.269 --> 10:11.564
[Brennan] <i>When you think about
Commodus, who had more, personally,</i>

10:11.565 --> 10:16.619
and more, historically, going
for him than any other human being

10:16.737 --> 10:19.247
<i>previous in the history
of human existence...</i>

10:19.906 --> 10:25.629
I mean, in fact, no Roman Emperor
for 80 years had had a son.

10:26.371 --> 10:29.174
<i>However, one would be very,
very hard pressed to find</i>

10:29.458 --> 10:31.459
<i>a less intellectually,</i>

10:31.460 --> 10:33.586
less energetic, less motivated

10:33.587 --> 10:37.599
<i>person with that type of responsibility
in the whole of human history.</i>

10:40.802 --> 10:43.938
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:04.101 --> 11:05.576
[narrator] <i>Against his will,</i>

11:05.577 --> 11:08.171
<i>Commodus has been called to Germania.</i>

11:08.330 --> 11:12.801
<i>Ordered to train under his father
to become the next Emperor.</i>

11:16.202 --> 11:18.390
<i>Hundreds of miles from Rome,</i>

11:18.590 --> 11:20.809
<i>along the borders of the Empire,</i>

11:21.093 --> 11:25.230
<i>massive armies of Germanic tribes
are invading Roman territory.</i>

11:26.098 --> 11:29.734
<i>And the Roman military has
been called to the front lines.</i>

11:40.153 --> 11:43.957
<i>With one of the strongest ground
and naval forces in the world,</i>

11:44.700 --> 11:46.310
<i>the Roman military is made up</i>

11:46.311 --> 11:49.903
<i>of hundreds of thousands
of highly trained soldiers,</i>

11:50.122 --> 11:52.674
<i>equipped with the latest weaponry,</i>

11:52.916 --> 11:55.668
<i>and prepared to defend
the Empire's borders...</i>

11:55.669 --> 11:57.387
<i>at all costs.</i>

11:59.131 --> 12:02.091
[Brennan] <i>There was the
problem of Rome's neighbors.</i>

12:02.092 --> 12:04.394
Both to the east, and to the north.

12:04.594 --> 12:05.928
The Parthians to the east

12:05.929 --> 12:08.940
<i>and Germanic tribes to the
north, which were a threat.</i>

12:11.309 --> 12:13.695
<i>Romans had been fighting Germans,</i>

12:14.938 --> 12:17.365
<i>at this point, for 250 years.</i>

12:19.568 --> 12:21.944
<i>And the border</i>

12:21.945 --> 12:24.196
on the Danube had always been a problem.

12:24.197 --> 12:26.666
And, in fact, as it turns
out, always would be a problem.

12:31.455 --> 12:32.538
[Holland] <i>The Roman army</i>

12:32.539 --> 12:36.417
was the most formidable fighting machine

12:36.418 --> 12:39.721
that the ancient world had seen.

12:41.006 --> 12:43.975
<i>The basis for their success</i>

12:44.384 --> 12:48.021
<i>was less their capacity for killing,</i>

12:49.681 --> 12:51.807
<i>and more their capacity
for entrenchment.</i>

12:51.808 --> 12:55.153
<i>It was a capacity for
digging fortresses,</i>

12:56.563 --> 13:02.369
for fashioning all the
infrastructure of a frontier force

13:02.527 --> 13:06.072
<i>that served to ensure
that the Roman frontiers</i>

13:06.073 --> 13:09.125
were essentially
guarded and held secure.

13:39.690 --> 13:41.741
[Cleander] Oh, Saoterus,
that's disgusting.

13:41.858 --> 13:44.610
I hope you learned your lesson.
You'll never outdrink me, my friend.

13:44.611 --> 13:47.163
- Never again.
- [Cleander laughs]

13:51.410 --> 13:52.961
Tell my father I'm here.

13:54.746 --> 13:56.715
Let's hope we're not
stuck here for too long.

14:18.478 --> 14:20.067
Come with me.

14:26.111 --> 14:27.611
[Prof. Clifford Ando] <i>Marcus
Aurelius and Commodus</i>

14:27.612 --> 14:30.749
have come down in history as
very, very different individuals.

14:31.700 --> 14:34.410
<i>After all, he was also a
leading general of his time</i>

14:34.411 --> 14:37.631
<i>and led many wars along
the Danube frontier.</i>

14:37.914 --> 14:41.292
Commodus probably was as
irresponsible as people say.

14:41.293 --> 14:45.713
<i>That said, Marcus Aurelius does not
appear to have shown any hesitation</i>

14:45.714 --> 14:48.391
in promoting Commodus
from a very young age.

14:48.675 --> 14:51.811
♪ ♪

15:09.279 --> 15:10.704
Where is he?

15:12.699 --> 15:14.000
[sigh]

15:35.889 --> 15:37.376
What?

16:12.175 --> 16:13.768
I promised your mother

16:14.136 --> 16:17.022
I'd try and do my best
to make a man of you.

16:17.305 --> 16:20.400
I never break my word. Ever.

16:21.601 --> 16:23.111
It begins now.

16:24.813 --> 16:26.990
You want me to train
like some common soldier?

16:46.752 --> 16:48.303
[grunting]

16:57.971 --> 16:59.314
Again.

17:28.710 --> 17:30.178
Again.

17:42.808 --> 17:44.067
Again.

18:03.996 --> 18:09.175
I'm going to show you what happens when
you don't know how to handle a sword.

18:21.096 --> 18:22.930
[Prof. Aaron Irvin] <i>One
of the great debates,</i>

18:22.931 --> 18:25.766
<i>not just among Roman
historians of today,</i>

18:25.767 --> 18:28.945
but even of the time, was why Commodus?

18:29.062 --> 18:31.531
Why did Marcus Aurelius choose Commodus?

18:32.065 --> 18:36.193
<i>Why, despite the fact that
everybody seemed to see</i>

18:36.194 --> 18:40.740
<i>that he was not up to this task,
why was there still the insistence</i>

18:40.741 --> 18:44.878
<i>that Commodus was going
to be the next Emperor?</i>

18:45.787 --> 18:48.497
<i>Perhaps we can chalk it up to naïveté</i>

18:48.498 --> 18:51.334
<i>or a kind of generic
just love for his son,</i>

18:51.335 --> 18:53.544
<i>blinding him to the realities</i>

18:53.545 --> 18:55.463
that his son was not up to the task.

18:55.464 --> 18:58.558
And his son was not
ready for this position.

19:20.947 --> 19:22.604
[Nichols] The means
through which Commodus

19:22.605 --> 19:26.035
was groomed and trained
to become Emperor

19:26.036 --> 19:29.047
<i>were unparalleled in Roman history.</i>

19:29.289 --> 19:33.093
<i>He had high hopes for his
son during this period.</i>

19:34.252 --> 19:38.848
What Marcus Aurelius imagined for
his child and what his child became

19:39.716 --> 19:42.185
<i>were two very different things.</i>

19:46.765 --> 19:48.933
[narrator] <i>As Commodus trains,</i>

19:48.934 --> 19:53.029
<i>the Germanic tribes begin to
push through Roman defenses,</i>

19:55.440 --> 19:59.536
<i>banding together and launching a
massive assault on the Roman army.</i>

20:00.112 --> 20:04.115
[Holland] <i>The great Roman nightmare</i>
<i>was of Northern Barbarians</i>

20:04.116 --> 20:06.918
<i>sweeping southwards and conquering Rome.</i>

20:10.706 --> 20:14.175
<i>In the reign of Marcus Aurelius,
there was a disturbance.</i>

20:14.292 --> 20:17.461
He knew that he had no
choice but to confront that.

20:17.462 --> 20:20.673
And as it turned out, the wars
that Marcus Aurelius fought

20:20.674 --> 20:23.101
<i>against the German people were</i>

20:23.593 --> 20:28.931
<i>as strenuous and challenging
as any Barbarian enemy</i>

20:28.932 --> 20:31.359
<i>that the Roman people had faced.</i>

20:33.353 --> 20:34.779
[narrator] <i>Lasting years...</i>

20:35.731 --> 20:37.949
<i>it's a devastating war.</i>

20:38.567 --> 20:41.453
<i>Killing thousands of men on both sides.</i>

20:53.373 --> 20:56.509
<i>The war also takes its
toll on the Emperor...</i>

20:56.793 --> 20:58.678
<i>who soon falls ill.</i>

21:00.213 --> 21:02.423
[Anthony Everitt] <i>Marcus
Aurelius spent most of his life</i>

21:02.424 --> 21:06.802
<i>dealing with, fighting,
trying to resist, coping with</i>

21:06.803 --> 21:11.900
Barbarian tribes pressing up
against the frontiers of the Empire.

21:12.934 --> 21:17.229
<i>And as the health of Marcus
Aurelius began to fade,</i>

21:17.230 --> 21:19.491
<i>there was a great deal of worrying.</i>

21:19.816 --> 21:23.652
He seems to have had problems
in his chest and stomach.

21:23.653 --> 21:25.196
It may have been cancer.

21:25.197 --> 21:28.625
It may have been something to do with
his heart. One doesn't really know.

21:40.796 --> 21:43.056
[narrator] <i>With the
Emperor's health diminishing,</i>

21:43.423 --> 21:45.642
<i>news is sent to the palace.</i>

21:50.889 --> 21:52.848
<i>But on its way back to Rome,</i>

21:52.849 --> 21:55.193
<i>the message is quickly distorted.</i>

21:57.354 --> 22:00.281
<i>And soon enough, it becomes a rumor...</i>

22:00.607 --> 22:03.493
<i>that Marcus Aurelius has died.</i>

22:08.448 --> 22:10.324
[Ando] <i>In the case of Marcus Aurelius,</i>

22:10.325 --> 22:13.336
<i>it seems quite clear that
rumors started to spread</i>

22:13.453 --> 22:15.130
<i>that the Emperor had died.</i>

22:15.414 --> 22:18.049
And sometimes these may
well have been engineered.

22:18.333 --> 22:22.336
<i>And what is crucial about this, is
that verification of these rumors</i>

22:22.337 --> 22:25.348
in the Roman world would have
been phenomenally difficult.

22:49.865 --> 22:51.407
[narrator] <i>Before long,</i>

22:51.408 --> 22:53.951
<i>the rumor of Marcus Aurelius's death</i>

22:53.952 --> 22:56.963
<i>reaches the most powerful
woman in the Empire...</i>

22:57.414 --> 22:59.299
<i>Empress Faustina.</i>

23:09.634 --> 23:12.345
[Jerry Toner] <i>Faustina was
Marcus Aurelius's wife.</i>

23:12.346 --> 23:14.638
She was the daughter
of the previous Emperor,

23:14.639 --> 23:16.232
Antoninus Pius.

23:17.059 --> 23:19.810
<i>And she was a successful
wife with Marcus,</i>

23:19.811 --> 23:21.771
<i>gave him children over that period.</i>

23:21.772 --> 23:27.452
So she must immediately have looked for
her safety and for her family's safety.

23:29.488 --> 23:32.615
[narrator] <i>Devastated by news</i>
<i>of her husband's death,</i>

23:32.616 --> 23:36.419
<i>Faustina fears her son
isn't ready for the throne,</i>

23:37.287 --> 23:42.175
<i>and knows she has to come up with a
plan before word reaches the Senate.</i>

23:50.092 --> 23:54.104
<i>The Roman Senate is made up of the
most influential men in the Empire.</i>

23:56.056 --> 24:01.277
<i>All looking for opportunities to
further their political careers.</i>

24:09.569 --> 24:12.571
[Brennan] <i>There were
clearly any number of folks</i>

24:12.572 --> 24:13.906
<i>in the Roman Senate</i>

24:13.907 --> 24:16.909
themselves, who were senators,
who thought that they had

24:16.910 --> 24:18.619
even better claim to nobility

24:18.620 --> 24:22.132
<i>or to the throne than the
reigning Emperor himself.</i>

24:22.499 --> 24:24.750
<i>In general, it seems
that being at the top</i>

24:24.751 --> 24:28.221
<i>was a very lonely and dangerous
place in Ancient Rome.</i>

24:33.427 --> 24:34.927
[narrator] <i>Throughout the Empire,</i>

24:34.928 --> 24:38.690
<i>governors and ambitious leaders
are determined to seize control.</i>

24:39.683 --> 24:44.112
<i>And a challenge to the throne could
come from any of the Empire's regions.</i>

24:45.063 --> 24:46.823
<i>With rumors quickly spreading,</i>

24:47.315 --> 24:50.118
<i>a power grab could soon take hold.</i>

24:56.491 --> 25:00.378
<i>The play for the throne puts
members of the royal family at risk.</i>

25:01.621 --> 25:03.956
<i>Including the Emperor's daughter...</i>

25:03.957 --> 25:05.508
<i>Lucilla.</i>

25:08.003 --> 25:10.930
<i>Married to her father's trusted advisor,</i>

25:11.631 --> 25:15.977
<i>Lucilla has already been
groomed for a life of influence.</i>

25:17.846 --> 25:19.638
[Irvin] <i>Lucilla had been</i>

25:19.639 --> 25:22.600
one of the oldest of
Marcus Aurelius's children

25:22.601 --> 25:24.694
who had survived into adulthood.

25:25.062 --> 25:27.730
<i>She had been involved in Roman politics,</i>

25:27.731 --> 25:31.034
<i>the back room deals, the administration.</i>

25:31.276 --> 25:33.027
So she was far more experienced.

25:33.028 --> 25:35.071
She had far better contacts.

25:35.072 --> 25:39.793
She had resources at her disposal
that Commodus didn't even know existed.

25:42.871 --> 25:45.674
[narrator] <i>But with the throne</i>
<i>being called into question,</i>

25:47.167 --> 25:50.804
<i>Lucilla knows her
ambitions are in jeopardy.</i>

25:51.338 --> 25:53.631
[Toner] <i>Lucilla was
Commodus's older sister</i>

25:53.632 --> 25:54.933
<i>12 years older.</i>

25:55.175 --> 26:00.397
And so she was used to having a place
at the top table in Roman society.

26:01.139 --> 26:03.516
<i>But she certainly seems to
have been slightly jealous</i>

26:03.517 --> 26:07.853
<i>of the increasingly powerful role
that her younger brother Commodus</i>

26:07.854 --> 26:09.322
<i>would have to inherit.</i>

26:18.782 --> 26:20.250
Here, take that.

26:21.743 --> 26:23.127
No.

26:23.578 --> 26:24.713
Yes.

26:27.874 --> 26:29.843
No one told me we were leaving.

26:30.752 --> 26:32.012
You've heard?

26:42.389 --> 26:43.606
Where are we going?

26:46.768 --> 26:48.486
I'm going to Egypt.

26:50.814 --> 26:52.407
You're staying here.

26:53.692 --> 26:55.869
We can't abandon Rome completely.

26:56.278 --> 26:58.246
And there are things I need to do,

26:58.780 --> 27:00.373
to secure our safety.

27:00.782 --> 27:02.250
In Egypt.

27:05.037 --> 27:06.963
You're seeing Avidius Cassius.

27:08.206 --> 27:10.166
I'm doing what I need to do

27:10.167 --> 27:12.218
to protect our family.

27:12.627 --> 27:14.387
So to protect Commodus,

27:14.921 --> 27:16.973
you'll leave me here by myself.

27:22.721 --> 27:24.314
I know it's dangerous.

27:27.684 --> 27:29.736
But what other choice do we have?

27:31.730 --> 27:33.031
My cloak.

27:33.940 --> 27:37.777
I will return as quickly as I can.

27:37.778 --> 27:40.497
We will all be together.
We will all be safe!

27:45.369 --> 27:46.670
Trust me.

27:49.289 --> 27:50.548
Go!

27:53.585 --> 27:55.836
[Prof. David Levene] <i>Any
member of the imperial family</i>

27:55.837 --> 28:00.007
<i>is potentially in danger
when the Emperor dies.</i>

28:00.008 --> 28:02.551
It is extremely common

28:02.552 --> 28:05.137
for emperors who fall from power

28:05.138 --> 28:08.441
to have their entire family wiped out.

28:45.095 --> 28:47.638
[narrator] <i>Determined
to protect her family</i>

28:47.639 --> 28:49.524
<i>and secure her own power,</i>

28:51.143 --> 28:53.820
<i>Faustina sets a plan in motion.</i>

28:54.062 --> 28:56.605
<i>Instead of waiting for an overthrow,</i>

28:56.606 --> 28:58.908
<i>the Empress plans to leave her city...</i>

28:59.359 --> 29:00.785
<i>immediately.</i>

29:06.074 --> 29:09.336
<i>Traveling more than 1,000 miles south...</i>

29:10.996 --> 29:15.550
<i>across the Mediterranean to one of
the Empire's furthest regions...</i>

29:19.212 --> 29:20.597
<i>Egypt.</i>

29:39.608 --> 29:42.160
<i>One of the wealthiest
territories in the world,</i>

29:44.696 --> 29:47.749
<i>Egypt is one of the
leading producers of grain,</i>

29:49.451 --> 29:53.713
<i>and is home to one of the largest
ports in the Northern Hemisphere.</i>

29:59.086 --> 30:02.973
<i>Guarded by more than
15,000 Roman soldiers,</i>

30:13.725 --> 30:17.570
<i>and run by the second most
powerful man in the Empire,</i>

30:18.355 --> 30:21.866
<i>Egyptian governor Avidius Cassius.</i>

30:26.863 --> 30:29.073
[Irvin] <i>Egypt was the personal territory</i>

30:29.074 --> 30:32.284
of the Emperor. It was
actually his estate,

30:32.285 --> 30:35.955
and Cassius was tasked with
keeping control of Egypt,

30:35.956 --> 30:39.801
essentially keeping control of
the Emperor's own private lands.

30:40.293 --> 30:42.169
<i>He had been trusted by the family.</i>

30:42.170 --> 30:44.306
<i>He had been in the inner circle.</i>

30:51.680 --> 30:53.014
[guard] Sir...

30:53.015 --> 30:54.774
the report you requested.

31:02.649 --> 31:04.942
I want you to double
the guards at the port.

31:04.943 --> 31:06.911
There's been some
pilfering of the grain.

31:07.320 --> 31:08.538
I'm not happy.

31:13.118 --> 31:14.711
- You can go.
- Sir.

32:08.215 --> 32:09.965
[Prof. Andrew Scott] <i>The
image we get out of Faustina</i>

32:09.966 --> 32:12.852
is one of untrustworthiness
and promiscuity.

32:13.011 --> 32:16.064
There are many rumors going
around about both of these areas.

32:17.265 --> 32:19.288
<i>And we can see a partial answer to that</i>

32:19.313 --> 32:22.970
<i>in Faustina's bid to Avidius Cassius,</i>

32:23.855 --> 32:25.382
where she thought
maybe she would be able

32:25.407 --> 32:27.858
to retain her position in the Empire,

32:27.859 --> 32:29.661
perhaps even as his wife.

32:39.162 --> 32:41.548
That was unexpected.

32:42.874 --> 32:44.217
Cassius,

32:45.085 --> 32:47.387
you've always been there for me

32:47.713 --> 32:49.931
ever since we were children.

32:52.759 --> 32:55.395
Now you're the only
one who can protect me.

32:57.472 --> 33:00.442
I think you might be overestimating me.

33:02.144 --> 33:03.486
How could I?

33:04.146 --> 33:05.062
Marcus always said

33:05.063 --> 33:08.408
you were the second most
powerful man in the Empire.

33:09.818 --> 33:11.786
You could be Emperor yourself,

33:12.738 --> 33:13.913
if you wanted.

33:14.740 --> 33:16.166
Emperor?

33:18.410 --> 33:20.629
With the strength of your armies

33:21.288 --> 33:23.840
and my name behind you,

33:24.374 --> 33:26.801
no one could stop you.

33:31.381 --> 33:33.850
Emperor of Rome.

33:39.264 --> 33:41.775
But you must promise me one thing.

33:42.100 --> 33:43.318
Anything.

33:44.019 --> 33:45.978
Protect my family.

33:45.979 --> 33:47.364
Commodus.

33:48.065 --> 33:49.866
As if he were your own.

34:04.623 --> 34:06.053
[Levene] <i>Allegedly, again,</i>

34:06.078 --> 34:09.960
<i>she had actually promised
to marry Avidius Cassius</i>

34:09.960 --> 34:11.962
after Marcus's presumed death

34:11.963 --> 34:16.226
in order to solidify
that transfer of power.

34:17.719 --> 34:20.137
<i>Because, if a power
vacuum had been left,</i>

34:20.138 --> 34:23.641
<i>that would've put Faustina and
everybody else around Marcus</i>

34:23.641 --> 34:26.319
<i>in an extremely perilous position.</i>

34:29.856 --> 34:33.618
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:39.282 --> 34:41.793
[narrator] <i>With Empress
Faustina's backing,</i>

34:41.868 --> 34:46.380
<i>Avidius Cassius raises an
army to march on Rome...</i>

34:46.665 --> 34:49.092
<i>and claim the throne for himself.</i>

34:53.880 --> 34:55.130
<i>Within months,</i>

34:55.132 --> 34:59.510
<i>he seizes control of major territories
in the eastern Roman Empire.</i>

34:59.511 --> 35:05.191
<i>And with support from leaders in
Egypt, Syria, Judaea, and Arabia,</i>

35:07.519 --> 35:10.613
<i>he makes the ultimate
move for the throne.</i>

35:13.358 --> 35:15.359
[Irvin] <i>Cassius declared
himself Emperor.</i>

35:15.360 --> 35:18.487
<i>Egypt declared him to
be the Emperor as well.</i>

35:18.488 --> 35:23.335
Two of the legions located within
Egypt declared Cassius for Emperor.

35:33.503 --> 35:37.182
<i>And then, it was gradually revealed
that Marcus Aurelius was still alive.</i>

35:39.009 --> 35:40.926
<i>That he hadn't passed away after all,</i>

35:40.927 --> 35:44.314
<i>that the messages had been
incorrectly interpreted.</i>

35:46.433 --> 35:47.516
<i>And now,</i>

35:47.517 --> 35:49.018
we have two rival Emperors.

35:49.019 --> 35:51.821
We have a potential civil
war within the Empire.

36:08.664 --> 36:12.217
[narrator] <i>As news of Aurelius'
recovery reaches Egypt,</i>

36:12.709 --> 36:17.764
<i>Empress Faustina knows she must
face her husband in Germania.</i>

36:19.716 --> 36:25.063
<i>While Avidius Cassius chooses to
continue his campaign for the throne.</i>

36:26.014 --> 36:28.891
[Levene] <i>Avidius Cassius,
I think, had little choice</i>

36:28.892 --> 36:31.987
but to continue with his campaign.

36:34.731 --> 36:36.774
<i>If he backed away at that point,</i>

36:36.775 --> 36:38.859
<i>then everybody's going to know,</i>

36:38.860 --> 36:41.654
<i>including Marcus, is going to know</i>

36:41.655 --> 36:46.459
<i>that he was ready to seize the
power from Marcus's own son,</i>

36:46.827 --> 36:51.172
<i>who was the closest person
in line for the succession.</i>

37:17.941 --> 37:20.618
[general] Avidius Cassius has
raised seven legions already.

37:21.278 --> 37:25.123
Three in Syria, two in Judaea,
one in Arabia, and one in Egypt.

37:25.824 --> 37:28.960
So only Cappadocia and
Bithynia have remained loyal.

37:30.037 --> 37:31.880
[general] If we split
our forces in half,

37:32.289 --> 37:35.333
we send ten legions across the
Mediterranean to Alexandria...

37:35.334 --> 37:37.543
No, no. Ten legions are not
enough to hold the front here.

37:37.544 --> 37:39.420
Our men would be
spread as far as Vetera.

37:39.421 --> 37:41.047
They'd be practically useless.

37:41.048 --> 37:42.298
With all due respect, Emperor,

37:42.299 --> 37:45.060
- your wife has put Rome...
- My wife has nothing to do with it.

37:45.218 --> 37:47.762
Mother? She's involved?

37:47.763 --> 37:49.022
No.

37:49.348 --> 37:51.191
Rumors only, nothing more.

37:53.310 --> 37:55.695
Listen, if we move the fifteenth north,

37:56.772 --> 37:57.947
to Dacia.

37:58.190 --> 37:59.482
We take the twelfth...

37:59.483 --> 38:02.452
♪ ♪

38:33.475 --> 38:36.820
[narrator] <i>After inadvertently
starting a war for the throne,</i>

38:37.354 --> 38:41.199
<i>Faustina knows she must
return to her husband...</i>

38:41.858 --> 38:45.453
<i>and try to maintain
her place as Empress.</i>

38:51.493 --> 38:54.713
[Irvin] <i>Faustina, unfortunately,</i>
<i>overplayed her hand.</i>

38:56.373 --> 38:59.333
The great women in Roman society

38:59.334 --> 39:01.877
always supported their
men, elevated their men,

39:01.878 --> 39:07.133
pushed the men that they represented
into greater positions of power,

39:07.134 --> 39:08.968
greater positions of competition,

39:08.969 --> 39:11.104
and helped to drive them forward.

39:13.015 --> 39:14.598
<i>We can see this playing out, of course,</i>

39:14.599 --> 39:17.652
<i>directly in the case of Avidius Cassius.</i>

39:18.061 --> 39:21.605
Where she clearly trusted him
and had every reason to believe

39:21.606 --> 39:24.358
that he would make a fantastic emperor.

39:24.359 --> 39:27.153
<i>Unfortunately, of course,
we have a miscommunication</i>

39:27.154 --> 39:30.749
<i>that ends up backfiring
on that entire situation.</i>

39:51.303 --> 39:52.937
I need to talk to my mother.

40:05.776 --> 40:07.661
The generals in there want you dead.

40:08.820 --> 40:11.873
By the Gods, how has this
gotten so out of control?

40:12.115 --> 40:13.833
I never intended this.

40:14.076 --> 40:15.377
Well is it true?

40:15.869 --> 40:17.462
Did you betray us?

40:19.081 --> 40:21.257
I thought your father was dead.

40:21.625 --> 40:23.802
I knew what that meant,

40:24.169 --> 40:25.971
how they would come for us.

40:27.005 --> 40:29.307
I was only trying to protect us,

40:29.925 --> 40:31.434
to protect you.

40:32.302 --> 40:34.229
So it was a misunderstanding.

40:34.805 --> 40:36.815
So tell Father that.

40:37.891 --> 40:39.484
He'll never believe me.

40:39.976 --> 40:42.153
It's the truth. Of
course he'll believe you.

40:44.523 --> 40:46.241
The truth...

40:46.858 --> 40:48.827
He'll understand. He has to.

41:34.698 --> 41:35.957
Is it true?

41:37.117 --> 41:39.878
- You know me better than that.
- That is not an answer.

41:42.289 --> 41:44.341
You think I'd betray my own family?

41:44.750 --> 41:45.967
My husband?

41:46.168 --> 41:48.803
I think someone can be
driven to do anything,

41:49.171 --> 41:50.722
when their life's in jeopardy.

41:51.673 --> 41:54.559
And some things are
beyond even imagining.

41:55.302 --> 41:57.011
Faustina. Tell me the truth.

41:57.012 --> 41:59.522
- I don't know what you want.
- I need the truth!

42:02.017 --> 42:05.487
You tell me plainly. Now.

42:09.316 --> 42:11.618
I've been faithful to you.

42:12.444 --> 42:13.953
Always.

42:16.406 --> 42:17.832
And these stories,

42:18.033 --> 42:21.577
concerning you and Avidius Cassius?

42:21.578 --> 42:23.338
They're lies.

42:24.665 --> 42:26.967
It's rumors...

42:27.876 --> 42:30.679
If there is one thing that's true,

42:30.879 --> 42:32.597
it's that I love you.

42:33.131 --> 42:36.518
And I would not do anything to hurt you.

42:37.260 --> 42:40.188
Anything else is a lie.

42:45.394 --> 42:47.570
I just needed to hear it

42:48.063 --> 42:49.781
from your own lips.

43:02.327 --> 43:03.795
Marcus.

43:07.708 --> 43:09.259
Protect Commodus.

43:36.653 --> 43:37.829
Sir...

43:50.125 --> 43:52.636
[Toner] <i>Being a Roman Emperor</i>
<i>was a difficult job.</i>

43:53.086 --> 43:54.670
<i>You are atop of a system</i>

43:54.671 --> 43:58.433
<i>that managed one of the largest
empires the world had ever known.</i>

43:59.384 --> 44:01.927
But there were also problems of loyalty.

44:01.928 --> 44:04.972
In such a big empire,
you need to delegate.

44:04.973 --> 44:06.640
But who can you trust?

44:06.641 --> 44:09.402
Can you trust even
members of your own family?

44:09.561 --> 44:11.237
Often, sadly, not.

45:35.689 --> 45:36.990
[groans]

45:41.945 --> 45:44.497
[gurgling]

46:05.844 --> 46:07.312
Mother...

